title: Modeling directly from antibody levels
text: Proposed model Two-component mixture model test result ZZ Zj(j={,S})Z_j (j = \{, S\}) latent mixing component density fj(zj|Œ∏j)f_j(z_j|\theta_j) œÄTRUE()\pi_{\text{TRUE}}() age-dependent mixing probability can represented f(z|zI,zS,)=(1‚àíœÄTRUE())fS(zS|Œ∏S)+œÄTRUE()fI(zI|Œ∏I) f(z|z_I, z_S,) = (1-\pi_{\text{TRUE}}())f_S(z_S|\theta_S)+\pi_{\text{TRUE}}()f_I(z_I|\theta_I) mean E(Z|)E(Z|) thus equals Œº()=(1‚àíœÄTRUE())ŒºS+œÄTRUE()ŒºI \mu() = (1-\pi_{\text{TRUE}}())\mu_S+\pi_{\text{TRUE}}()\mu_I true prevalence can calculated œÄTRUE()=Œº()‚àíŒºSŒºI‚àíŒºS \pi_{\text{TRUE}}() = \frac{\mu() - \mu_S}{\mu_I - \mu_S} Force infection can calculated ŒªTRUE=Œº‚Ä≤()ŒºI‚àíŒº() \lambda_{TRUE} = \frac{\mu'()}{\mu_I - \mu()} Fitting data fit mixture data, use mixture_model function  sero-prevalence FOI can esimated using function estimate_from_mixture
code: df <- vzv_be_2001_2003[vzv_be_2001_2003$age < 40.5,] df <- df[order(df$age),] data <- df$VZVmIUml model <- mixture_model(antibody_level = data) #> Warning in mix(data, starting_values, dist = "norm"): The optimization process #> terminated because either the estimates are approximate local optimal solution #> or steptol is too small model$info #>  #> Parameters: #>       pi    mu  sigma #> 1 0.1088 2.349 0.6804 #> 2 0.8912 6.439 0.9437 #>  #> Distribution: #> [1] "norm" #>  #> Constraints: #>    conpi    conmu consigma  #>   "NONE"   "NONE"   "NONE" plot(model) est_mixture <- estimate_from_mixture(df$age, data, mixture_model = model, threshold_status = df$seropositive, sp=83, monotonize = FALSE) plot(est_mixture) #> Warning: No shared levels found between `names(values)` of the manual scale and the #> data's fill values.

title: Parametric models
text: Proposed model Farrington‚Äôs model, force infection defined non-negative Œª()‚â•0\lambda() \geq 0 increases peak linear fashion followed exponential decrease Œª()=(Œ±a‚àíŒ≥)e‚àíŒ≤a+Œ≥ \lambda() = (\alpha - \gamma)e^{-\beta } + \gamma Œ≥\gamma called long term residual FOI, ‚Üí‚àû\rightarrow \infty , Œª()‚ÜíŒ≥\lambda () \rightarrow \gamma Integrating Œª()\lambda() results following non-linear model prevalence $$ \pi () = 1 - e^{-\int_0^\lambda(s) ds} \\ = 1 - exp\{ \frac{\alpha}{\beta}ae^{-\beta } + \frac{1}{\beta}(\frac{\alpha}{\beta} - \gamma)(e^{-\beta } - 1) -\gamma \} $$ Fitting data Use farrington_model() fit Farrington‚Äôs model.
code: rubella <- rubella_uk_1986_1987 rubella$neg <- rubella$tot - rubella$pos  farrington_md <- farrington_model(    rubella$age, pos = rubella$pos, tot = rubella$tot,    start=list(alpha=0.07,beta=0.1,gamma=0.03)    ) plot(farrington_md)

title: Semiparametric model
text: Proposed model general model relating prevalence age can written GLM \[ g(P(Y_i = 1| _i)) = g(\pi(a_i)) = \eta(a_i) \] \(g\) link function \(\eta\) linear predictor linear predictor can estimated semi-parametrically using penalized spline truncated power basis functions degree \(p\) fixed knots \(\kappa_1,..., \kappa_k\) followed \[ \eta(a_i) = \beta_0 + \beta_1a_i + ... + \beta_p a_i^p + \Sigma_{k=1}^ku_k(a_i - \kappa_k)^p_+ \] \[ (a_i - \kappa_k)^p_+ = \begin{cases} 0, & a_i \le \kappa_k \\ (a_i - \kappa_k)^p, & a_i > \kappa_k \end{cases} \] matrix notation, mean structure model \(\eta(a_i)\) becomes \[ \eta = X\beta + Zu \] \(\eta = [\eta(a_i) ... \eta(a_N) ]^T\), \(\beta = [\beta_0 \beta_1 .... \beta_p]^T\), \(u = [u_1 u_2 ... u_k]^T\) regression corresponding design matrices \[ X = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & a_1 & a_1^2 & ... & a_1^p \\ 1 & a_2 & a_2^2 & ... & a_2^p \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \dots & \vdots \\ 1 & a_N & a_N^2 & ... & a_N^p \end{bmatrix}, Z = \begin{bmatrix} (a_1 - \kappa_1 )_+^p & (a_1 - \kappa_2 )_+^p & \dots & (a_1 - \kappa_k)_+^p \\ (a_2 - \kappa_1 )_+^p & (a_2 - \kappa_2 )_+^p & \dots & (a_2 - \kappa_k)_+^p \\ \vdots & \vdots & \dots & \vdots \\ (a_N - \kappa_1 )_+^p & (a_N - \kappa_2 )_+^p & \dots & (a_N - \kappa_k)_+^p \end{bmatrix} \] FOI can derived \[ \hat{\lambda}(a_i) = [\hat{\beta_1} , 2\hat{\beta_2}a_i, ..., p \hat{\beta} a_i ^{p-1} + \Sigma^k_{k=1} p \hat{u}_k(a_i - \kappa_k)^{p-1}_+] \delta(\hat{\eta}(a_i)) \] \(\delta(.)\) determined link function use model

title: Semiparametric model
text: Refer Chapter 8.2.1 Proposed approach first approach fit model maximizing following penalized likelihood : \(X\beta + Zu\) linear predictor (refer ??) \(D\) known semi-definite penalty matrix (Wahba 1978), (Green Silverman 1993) \(y\) response vector 1 unit vector, \(c(.)\) determined link function used \(\lambda\) smoothing parameter (larger values ‚Äì> smoother curves) \(\phi\) overdispersion parameter equals 1 overdispersion Fitting data fit data using penalized likelihood framework, specify framework = "pl" Basis function can defined via s parameter, values s includes: "tp" thin plate regression splines "cr" cubic regression splines "ps" P-splines proposed (Eilers Marx 1996) "ad" Adaptive smoothers options, refer mgcv documentation (Wood 2017)
code: data <- parvob19_be_2001_2003 pl <- penalized_spline_model(data$age, status = data$seropositive, s = "tp", framework = "pl")  pl$info #>  #> Family: binomial  #> Link function: logit  #>  #> Formula: #> spos ~ s(age, bs = s, sp = sp) #>  #> Estimated degrees of freedom: #> 6.16  total = 7.16  #>  #> UBRE score: 0.1206458 plot(pl)

title: Semiparametric model
text: Refer Chapter 8.2.2 Proposed approach Looking back (1), constraint \(u\) \(\Sigma_ku_k^2 < C\) positive value \(C\) equivalent choosing \((\beta, u)\) maximise (1) \(D = diag(0, 1)\) \(0\) denotes zero vector length \(p+1\) 1 denotes unit vector length \(K\) fixed value \(\lambda\) equivalent fitting following generalized linear mixed model Ngo Wand (2004) \[ f(y|u) = exp\{ \phi^{-1} [y^T(X\beta + Zu) - c(X\beta + Zu)] + 1^Tc(y)\},\\ u \sim N(0, G) \] similar notations \(G = \sigma^2_uI_{K \times K}\) Thus \(Z\) penalized assuming corresponding coefficients \(u\) random effect \(u \sim N(0, \sigma^2_uI)\). Fitting data fit data using penalized likelihood framework, specify framework = "glmm"
code: data <- parvob19_be_2001_2003 glmm <- penalized_spline_model(data$age, status = data$seropositive, s = "tp", framework = "glmm")  #>  #>  Maximum number of PQL iterations:  20 #> iteration 1 #> iteration 2 #> iteration 3 #> iteration 4 glmm$info$gam #>  #> Family: binomial  #> Link function: logit  #>  #> Formula: #> spos ~ s(age, bs = s, sp = sp) #>  #> Estimated degrees of freedom: #> 6.45  total = 7.45 plot(glmm)

u (t) - \mu (t) - \alpha (t)  \  rac{dR(t)}{dt} =  B(t) p + 
u (t) - \mu R(t) \end{cases} : B(t)=ŒºN(t)B(t) = \mu N(t) Œª(t)=Œ≤I(t)\lambda(t) =  eta (t) Œ≤ eta transmission rate Œº\mu natural death rate ŒΩ

code: state <- c(S=4999, I=1, R=0) parameters <- c(   mu=1/75, # 1 divided by life expectancy (75 years old)   alpha=0, # no disease-related death   beta=0.0005, # transmission rate   nu=1, # 1 year for infected to recover   p=0 # no vaccination at birth ) times <- seq(0, 250, by=0.1) model <- sir_basic_model(times, state, parameters) model$parameters #>         mu      alpha       beta         nu          p  #> 0.01333333 0.00000000 0.00050000 1.00000000 0.00000000 plot(model)

title: SIR model
text: Proposed model Extends SIR model interacting sub-populations (different age groups) K subpopulations, WAIFW matrix mixing matrix given C=[Œ≤11Œ≤12...Œ≤1KŒ≤21Œ≤22...Œ≤2K‚ãÆ‚ãÆ...‚ãÆŒ≤K1Œ≤K2...Œ≤KK] C = \begin{bmatrix}  \beta_{11} & \beta_{12}  & ... & \beta_{1K} \\ \beta_{21} & \beta_{22}  & ... & \beta_{2K} \\ \vdots & \vdots  & ... & \vdots \\ \beta_{K1} & \beta_{K2}  & ... & \beta_{KK} \\ \end{bmatrix} system differential equations ithth subpopulation given {dSi(t)dt=‚àí(‚àëj=1KŒ≤ijIj(t))Si(t)+NiŒºi‚àíŒºiSi(t)dIi(t)dt=(‚àëj=1KŒ≤ijIj(t))Si(t)‚àí(ŒΩi+Œºi)Ii(t)dRi(t)dt=ŒΩiIi(t)‚àíŒºiRi(t) \begin{cases} \frac{dS_i(t)}{dt} = -(\sum^K_{j=1}\beta_{ij}I_j(t)) S_i(t) + N_i\mu_i - \mu_i S_i(t) \\ \frac{dI_i(t)}{dt} = (\sum^K_{j=1}\beta_{ij}I_j(t)) S_i(t)  - (\nu_i + \mu_i) I_i(t)  \\ \frac{dR_i(t)}{dt} = \nu_i I_i(t)  - \mu_i R_i(t) \end{cases} FItting data fit SIR model subpopulations, use sir_subpops_model() specify following parameters state - initial proportion compartment population beta_matrix - WAIFW matrix times - time sequence parameters - parameters model
code: k <- 2 # number of population state <- c(   # proportion of each compartment for each population   s = c(0.8, 0.6),    i = c(0.2, 0.4),   r = c(  0,   0) ) beta_matrix <- c(   c(0.05, 0.00),   c(0.00, 0.05) ) parameters <- list(   beta = matrix(beta_matrix, nrow=k, ncol=k, byrow=TRUE),   nu = c(1/30, 1/30),   mu = 0.001,   k = k ) times<-seq(0,10000,by=0.5) model <- sir_subpops_model(times, state, parameters) model$parameters #> $beta #>      [,1] [,2] #> [1,] 0.05 0.00 #> [2,] 0.00 0.05 #>  #> $nu #> [1] 0.03333333 0.03333333 #>  #> $mu #> [1] 0.001 #>  #> $k #> [1] 2 plot(model) # returns plot for each population #> $subpop_1 #>  #> $subpop_2

text: Load rubella UK dataset. Find power best second degree fractional polynomial monotonicity constraint logit link function. power appears (-0.9,-0.9). Finally, fit second degree fractional polynomial.

title: Hepatitis C serological data from Belgium in 2006 (line listing) ‚Äî hcv_be_2006
code: # Reproduce Fig 4.3, p. 66 library(dplyr) # snapping age to aggregated age group # (credit: https://stackoverflow.com/a/12861810) groups <- c(0.5:24.5) range <- 0.5 low <- findInterval(hcv_be_2006$dur, groups) high <- low + 1 low_diff <- hcv_be_2006$dur - groups[ifelse(low == 0, NA, low)] high_diff <- groups[ifelse(high == 0, NA, high)] - hcv_be_2006$dur mins <- pmin(low_diff, high_diff, na.rm = TRUE) pick <- ifelse(!is.na(low_diff) & mins == low_diff, low, high) hcv_be_2006$dur <- ifelse(   mins <= range + .Machine$double.eps, groups[pick], hcv_be_2006$dur ) hcv_be_2006 <- hcv_be_2006 %>%   group_by(dur) %>%   summarise(tot = n(), pos = sum(seropositive))  plot(   hcv_be_2006$dur, hcv_be_2006$pos / hcv_be_2006$tot,   cex = 0.1 * hcv_be_2006$tot, pch = 16,   xlab = "duration of injection (years)",   ylab = "seroprevalence", xlim = c(0, 25), ylim = c(0, 1) )

what: serosv: model infectious disease parameters ‚Äî serosv-package
title: serosv: model infectious disease parameters ‚Äî serosv-package
text: easy--use efficient tool estimate infectious diseases parameters using serological data. Implemented models include SIR models (basic_sir_model(), static_sir_model(), mseir_model(), sir_subpops_model()), parametric models (polynomial_model(), fp_model()), nonparametric models (lp_model()), semiparametric models (penalized_splines_model()), hierarchical models (hierarchical_bayesian_model()) package based book "Modeling Infectious Disease Parameters Based Serological Social Contact Data: Modern Statistical Perspective" (Hens, Niel & Shkedy, Ziv & Aerts, Marc & Faes, Christel & Damme, Pierre & Beutels, Philippe., 2013) doi:10.1007/978-1-4614-4072-7 .
